{
  "abstract": {
    "summary": "The study investigated the effect of different polymers (Eudragit RS PO and Kollidon SR) on the release profile and bio-adhesive strength of ciprofloxacin HCl from co-matrix tablets. Tablets were prepared by direct compression. Bio-adhesion was measured using an in vitro wash-off method. Results showed Eudragit RS PO tablets released a greater percentage of drug, while Kollidon SR and xanthan gum provided better bio-adhesive strength. Xanthan gum was identified as a suitable synergist for controlled release, meeting USP specifications."
  },
  "introduction": {
    "background": "Orally administered controlled release dosage forms face challenges like short gastric retention time (GRT) and unpredictable gastric emptying. Bio-adhesive systems are explored to prolong GI residence time and improve site-specific drug absorption. Matrix systems using polymers are common for sustained release. Polymers can be insoluble/skeleton matrices or hydrophobic/erodible materials. Drug release mechanisms include diffusion, degradation, and swelling. Hydrophobic polymers can control release and enhance mucosal retention."
  },
